Cyclists, hikers, and birders can now enjoy the accessible Adirondack Rail Trail in New York. The old railway route provides visitors with multiple connecting trails to explore and an opportunity to visit the small communities and serene spots found along the way, like Lake Placid.   
The 34-mile Adirondack Rail Trail‚Äîfor cyclists, hikers, and birders‚Äîwinds through open wilderness while connecting scenic towns like Lake Placid, Tupper Lake, and Saranac Lake.&nbsp;

The Adirondack Rail Trail‚Äîwhich follows the old¬†Remsen-Lake Rail corridor¬†is a 34-mile accessible path that runs through the heart of¬†Adirondack Park¬†in New York State. Two-thirds (25 miles) of the trail is open to bikers, runners, hikers, and birders, providing access to breathtaking trails, numerous campsites, and waterway‚Ä¶

